Female (micropterous) . At first glance, quite different from male due to micropterous condition (
Fig. 48
).

Head ( Figs. 48 , 68 ,
79
) approximately 1.5 times longer than width across eyes, 1.2 times longer than pronotum. Eye ( Figs. 68 , 79 ) small, approximately 0.25 times as wide as interocular space in dorsal view. Antennal segment I much stouter than that of male, approximately 5 times longer than its maximum width, as long as segment II (
Figs. 102, 103
); flagellum 1.1 times longer than segment I (
Fig. 104
